{"contentApi":{"id":"media/greenslade/2012/dec/17/newtown-shooting-newspapers","sectionId":"media","sectionName":"Media","webPublicationDate":1355736720000,"webTitle":"How Newtown's weekly paper coped with reporting the school massacre","webUrl":"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/greenslade/2012/dec/17/newtown-shooting-newspapers","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/media/greenslade/2012/dec/17/newtown-shooting-newspapers","fields":{"trailText":"<p>Associate editor, and firefighter, was one of the first to the scene</p>","headline":"How Newtown's weekly paper coped with reporting the school massacre","body":"<p><a href=\"http://newtownbee.com/\">The Newtown Bee</a> is a classic example of a small-town American newspaper - a weekly with a long history of publishing the humdrum activities of a prosperous and growing community in Connecticut. </p><p>So how did the paper cope when confronted with one of the biggest tragedies in modern American history, the massacre of 20 children and seven adults? </p><p><a href=\"http://www.poynter.org/latest-news/mediawire/198433/how-the-newtown-bee-is-covering-community-school-shooting/\">Poynter starts its story behind the story</a> by telling how the Bee's associate editor, Shannon Hicks, was at the paper's offices when she heard about a possible shooting at Sandy Hook school.</p><p>As a volunteer firefighter, she was alerted through the police scanner and was one of the first people to arrive at the scene because the fire station shares a driveway with the school.</p><p>Her colleague, John Voket, told Poynter that she was just behind the first dozen police officers to arrive and began taking photographs immediately through the windscreen of her car, with one hand on the steering wheel and the other holding her camera.</p><figure><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2012/12/17/1355736711467/newtown.Shooting.jpg' alt='Newt' width='460' height='276' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>Shannon Hicks's picture of children being shepherded away from Sandy Hook school. Courtesy of The Newtown Bee via Reuters </figcaption></figure><p>This early photo of distressed children being evacuated from the school appeared <a href=\"http://www.poynter.org/latest-news/mediawire/198386/school-shooting-headlines-show-the-power-of-a-single-word/\">on many US newspaper front pages</a> and several papers across the world, including The Guardian <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2012/dec/14/newtown-shooting-gunman-kills-20-children\">here</a>. </p><p>The Associated Press distributed the picture after contacting the Bee. Hicks was told by her mother that it had been on the front page of Saturday's New York Times but was unaware of its ubiquitous use elsewhere. </p><p>Aware of the possibility of being accused of intrusion, she said later:</p><blockquote><p>\"I'm conflicted. I don't want people to be upset with me… It's harder when it's in your hometown and these are children we're gonna watch grow up, the ones who made it. </p><p>I know people are gonna be upset, but at the same time I felt I was doing something important.\"</p></blockquote><p>About 20 minutes after Hicks first arrived at the scene, Voket turned up and she passed the editorial baton to him in order to take up her firefighter role.</p><p>\"I literally put on my firefighter gear,\" she said. \"I was there as a firefighter probably for not even more than 20 minutes before my editor said he wanted me back in the office to work with him to coordinate coverage from there.\"</p><p>Hicks returned to the Bee while Voket remained at the school. He explained: \"We operate a little differently because our job is to take care of the community so we were inside helping to comfort victims and trying to provide human support without necessarily making reporting the number one priority.</p><p>\"The publisher came down to comfort some of the families a little later in the day.\"</p><p>R. Scudder Smith, is the third generation of his family to run the paper that his grandfather acquired in 1881, some four years after it was founded. He has been publisher of the weekly since 1973 and oversees a full-time editorial staff of eight. The Bee circulates to about two-thirds of a community that numbers 29,000.</p><p>At the time of the shooting, the paper had already published its latest weekly edition, including a front page report on how well Newtown schools were meeting state standards.</p><p>So, to relay news about the shooting, the paper used its website. But the site, unused to  the traffic surge, crashed multiple times. Voket said the Bee eventually acquired \"an intermediary service to supersize our bandwidth.\" </p><p>Meanwhile, the staff used social media to spread information about school lockdowns, re-routed traffic, and grief counselling. Now it has produced a special edition for today.</p><p>Hicks is not sure what's next for the staff. Voket told her: \"Pace yourself, because we don't think we're going to get much of a break… It's going to be days and nights of trying to stay current.\"</p><p><em>Sources:</em> <a href=\"http://www.poynter.org/latest-news/mediawire/198433/how-the-newtown-bee-is-covering-community-school-shooting/\">Poynter</a></p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/401190375|2012-12-22T11:49:04Z|6e1b3f208205463f0a878e7fd5e82b3aa5b04360 -->","showInRelatedContent":"true","lastModified":"2012-12-17T09:40:46Z","hasStoryPackage":"false","score":"1.0","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3chht","commentable":"true","internalContentCode":"401190375","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Roy Greenslade","publication":"guardian.co.uk","internalPageCode":"1843389","shouldHideAdverts":"true","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2012-12-24T09:32:00Z"},"tags":[{"id":"media/greenslade","type":"blog","sectionId":"media","sectionName":"Media","webTitle":"Greenslade","webUrl":"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/greenslade","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/media/greenslade","r